<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-010-315 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 500 736</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 18 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: govt told to drop GATT. (General Agreement on Tariffsand Trade)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McNamara, Sean.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Political IssuesGovernment RegulationAustraliaInternational tradeAustralian Electrical and Electronic Manufacturers AssociationTrade and professional associations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Australia: Govt Told To Drop GATT 11/18/91 CANBERRA, AUSTRALIA, 1991 NOV 18(NB) -- The Australian informationandM;technology (IT) and electronics industries faces a severe handicap since theAustralian Government has followed the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade(GATT) to the letter, the Australian Electrical and Electronic ManufacturersAssociation (AEEMA) has claimed.andM;The submission AEEMA made to the Industry Commission claimed many nationswere simply paying &quot;lip service&quot; to GATT, and that, were Australia to followthe agreement, Australian products would be at a distinct disadvantagecompeting against these nations' products.andP;  The submission says, &quot;Until ourmajor trading partners are prepared to demonstrate a similar commitment tothe GATT, Australia should lookandM;after its own interests first.andM;AEEMA, which includes IBM, Alcatel, and Ericsson among its 250 members, feelsthat the Australian IT trade deficit of AUS$4B per year is ample proof thatAustralia has failed to take advantage of the opportunities provided by themarket, and that further neglect by the government can only hurt.andP;  Althoughit sees no real role for the protectionism of the 1950s and 60s it feelsthere is a real place for positive policies from governments.andM;(Sean McNamara/19911115)</TEXT></DOC>